bout 1131–about 1180":"about 1131–about 1180","1131–1180":"1131–1180","1141–Female":"1141–Deceased","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1106–Male":"1106–Deceased","1098–Female":"1098–Deceased","1106":"1106","about 1180":"about 1180","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1252":"1252","1131":"1131","1141":"1141","about 1165":"about 1165","about 1131":"about 1131","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Southern French: variant of   St  .   Romain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Romain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Altagrace, Aurore, Camille, Dominique, Edele, Georges, Henri, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Jean-Michel, Jeanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Clair","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the male personal name <i>Clair</i> (from Latin <i>Clarus</i> ‘illustrious’), which was borne by two early Christian saints, a 3rd-century bishop of Nantes and the 4th-century St. Clair of Aquitaine.","French: nickname for a cheerful individual, from the adjective <i>clair</i> ‘bright, light’. Compare   Leclair   1.","American shortened form of French   Leclair   1, a cognate of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Leclair","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Emile, Normand, Gaston, Adrien, Antoine, Lucien, Monique, Philias, Camille.","French: nickname for a cheerful individual, a variant of   Clair   2 ‘bright, light’, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Derivation from the male personal name   Clair   1 is also possible. Compare   Laclair  ,   Laclaire  , and   Leclear  .","French: altered form of   Leclerc   1."]},{"name":"Klar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Ezriel, Tzvi, Baruch, Devorah, Isadore, Nachman, Yitzchok.  German Gerhard, Johann, Erhard, Kurt, Willibald.","German: nickname from Middle High German and Middle Low German <i>klār</i> ‘pure, beautiful, clear’.","German: from the female personal name <i>Klara</i>, an equivalent of <i>Clara</i> (see   Clair   and   Sinclair  )."]},{"name":"Cler","meanings":["French: variant of   Clair  ."]},{"name":"Clarin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luz, Alejandro, Armida, Epifano, Florencio, Jose, Libia, Librada, Maria Luisa, Raul, Santos, Sergio.","Swedish: variant of <b>Klarin</b>, ornamental or perhaps habitational name formed with <i>klar</i> ‘clear’ (possibly representing an element of a placename) + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’.","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Clair  ."]},{"name":"Auclair","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Raoul, Andre, Fernand, Ovila, Alphonse, Cecile, Gaston, Germaine, Jacques, Jean-Paul.","French: patronymic from   Clair  , from <i>(fils) au Clair</i> ‘(son) of Clair’. Compare   Leclerc   2 and   Oclair  .","History: Pierre and André Auclair, two brothers from Saint-Vivien near La Rochelle in France, are recorded in Charlesbourg, QC, in 1679 and 1681, respectively, the years of their marriage. The descendants of one or another brother also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Leclerc</i>, <i>Oclair</i>, and <i>O'Clair</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henri de St Clair was born about 1131, in Scotland, his father, Henry de St. Clair The Crusader, was 27 and his mother, Rosabel de Strathearn, was 34. He married Margaret Grathaway about 1165, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1180, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1131–about 1180":"umbes 1131–umbes 1180","1131–1180":"1131–1180","1141–Female":"1141–Surnud","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1106–Male":"1106–Surnud","1098–Female":"1098–Surnud","1106":"1106","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1252":"1252","1131":"1131","1141":"1141","about 1165":"umbes 1165","about 1131":"umbes 1131","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1131–about 1180":"noin 1131–noin 1180","1131–1180":"1131–1180","1141–Female":"1141–Kuollut","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1106–Male":"1106–Kuollut","1098–Female":"1098–Kuollut","1106":"1106","about 1180":"noin 1180","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1252":"1252","1131":"1131","1141":"1141","about 1165":"noin 1165","about 1131":"noin 1131","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1131–about 1180":"environ 1131–environ 1180","1131–1180":"1131–1180","1141–Female":"1141–Décédée","1165–1252":"1165–1252","1106–Male":"1106–Décédé","1098–Female":"1098–Décédée","1106":"1106","about 1180":"environ 1180","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1252":"1252","1131":"1131","1141":"1141","about 1165":"environ 1165","about 1131":"environ 1131","1180":"1180","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Henri de St Clair est né environ 1131, à Écosse, son père, Henry de St. Clair The Crusader, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Rosabel de Strathearn, avait 34 ans. Il a épousé Margaret Grathaway environ 1165, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est